While examining the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I reviewed all fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These films primarily utilize creative editing techniques to create illusions. My analysis concentrated on describing the poetic elements common to most trick films while also exploring the evolutionary anomalies present in some later examples. Generally, trick films from the turn of the century were characterized by their set-based nature, frontal proscenium composition, static camera work, use of long and medium shots, and adherence to the one-shot-equals-one-film principle. However, some films from the early twentieth century began challenging these conventions by incorporating elements like multiple shots.

A striking common feature among these trick films is their indoor set filming within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera maintains a fixed position rather than following the movement of figures or objects. This compositional approach, deeply rooted in theatrical traditions and particularly influenced by vaudeville and magic performances, was widespread in early cinema. The stage-based setup typically restricted movement to lateral directions, with characters rarely approaching or retreating from the camera. This is exemplified in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), where actors enter from stage right and move horizontally, with the camera remaining stationary even when they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium style naturally led to the predominance of long shots and occasional medium shots. Close-ups are notably absent from all Edison catalog trick films. This approach mirrors theatrical presentation, where audiences view the entire performance within the stage's boundaries. The middle-ground positioning of actors, who seldom approach the camera, precluded the development of close-up shots.

Typically, early trick films followed a one-concept-equals-one-film structure, resulting in films lasting roughly a minute or less, depending on frame rate. This format limited narrative possibilities, with most films featuring brief vaudeville-style illusions such as magic tricks, disappearances, and transformations with minimal storyline. Importantly, while these films appear as single shots to viewers, they often comprise multiple physical shots cleverly joined to create illusions. This is evident in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), where careful observation reveals the splice point where the shot with the severed "head" begins, though the film appears as one continuous take to the audience.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" represents, both in essence and name, an "oxymoron of 'Old-New'" as Ian Watt explains in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic style has experienced both contempt and admiration, faced accusations of superficiality while being celebrated for its ability to evoke what Burke called the 'terrible sublime.' Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, considered the original Gothic novel, merged elements from both "ancient and modern" romances to pioneer the Gothic genre and establish a new form of literary expression. Walpole combines "old" theatrical elements with 'new' naturalistic approaches found in 'modern' novels to create what he terms "A Gothic Story."

The Gothic genre heavily draws from medieval theatrical traditions, architectural elements, and cultural customs. By the time The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" had already been applied to various peoples, styles, and historical periods, often carrying connotations of being outdated or unsophisticated compared to "modern" social and literary "progress." The genre's enduring appeal stems from its unique fusion of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's innovative format, which offers readers intimate access to character psychology. This combination allows Gothic literature to feel simultaneously timeless and fresh, even to readers far removed from its original context.

The concept of Chivalry stands as one of the most significant medieval elements present in Gothic novels. In The Castle of Otranto, the medieval ideals of chivalry and knightly training are both preserved and transformed. Gothic writers, particularly Walpole, emphasized chivalric themes partly because they perceived their own society as lacking in these idealized qualities of honor, bravery, and competence. Through the lens of chivalric concepts, the "gothic past" becomes romanticized, foreshadowing the later evolution toward Romanticism, and serves as a mirror for contemporary social criticism. Walpole, writing during politically turbulent times, may have viewed the supposed moral integrity of the gothic era as something lost to his contemporary society. This perspective manifests clearly in characters like Frederic, who embodies traditional chivalric traits through his portrayal as a noble prince who has endured suffering and tragedy, reportedly meeting his end at the hands of infidels. The characterization of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is deliberately exaggerated, introducing the Gothic trope of excess that would become characteristic of the genre.

Supply chain management encompasses the sequence of processes involved in moving goods from customer order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the end customer. The term "supply chain management" was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. He described it as the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling supply chain operations to satisfy customer needs quickly and efficiently. A supply chain consists of six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these six key elements to deliver optimal customer service.

Production serves as the foundation and initial step in the supply chain process. It determines the when, why, where, and how of all manufacturing activities. Managers must understand customer preferences, primarily by analyzing market trends - the most significant indicator of customer demand. Once management has assessed market demands, they can determine product types and quantities. They then select optimal production facilities based on volume capabilities and quality standards, while ensuring customer satisfaction. The final production considerations involve workflow scheduling and equipment maintenance. Production is crucial to the supply chain, and careful attention to detail is essential to avoid costly time and resource waste. For instance, major retailers like Walmart and Target implement detailed protocols for every business aspect, from employee uniforms to shipment receiving, ensuring smooth operations through clear directives and expectations.

The second key element, supply, involves making strategic decisions about facility core capabilities and establishing appropriate outsourcing partnerships. A single product may involve multiple production divisions, each with distinct equipment, workforce, and specializations. Managers must determine the most suitable division for different production processes and may opt for outsourcing to achieve velocity - the ability to maintain quality and flexibility while minimizing or controlling costs.

Victorian novels are distinguished by their meticulous attention to detail and their emphasis on the period's aristocracy. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights." Both works incorporate elements of mystery and an inclination toward the bizarre, uncommon for novels of this era, which serves to strengthen the characters in each work while providing deeper insights into their motivations and emotional states.

"And now, waves of bewildering and confusing thoughts flooded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing furiously: for the very words they spoke echoed in his ears; and when he managed to catch his own attention... he discovered he was speaking to them.... Suddenly, he recoiled at the sound of gunfire; loud screams and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything became noise and chaos, as some invisible hand hurriedly carried him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uncomfortable sensation of pain, which ceaselessly tormented him."

A few years ago, I worked as a tutor in an after-school program for elementary school students. I did my best to help them in all subjects they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the teachers recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant difficulties with reading. I realized something wasn't quite right; he was experiencing the most unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all - it was quite puzzling. While he was clearly of Latino heritage, the boy spoke flawless English.

Things continued this way until I met his mother. I was supervising a few remaining students while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when she came in. His mother didn't speak any English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish knowledge (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it hit me like lightning: Adrian could read well enough, he just wasn't familiar with the English alphabet.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier challenges in schools, particularly in California, and to show that these issues aren't always obvious. Even for children who speak perfect English, reading can present significant obstacles. While we all acknowledge this problem exists, what's the solution? In Adrian's case, it was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex.

There's no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, ESL classes - none of these approaches alone will solve the problem. The key lies in combining all these methods! The dual language system, in particular, is an excellent approach - not just for native Spanish speakers, but for all children. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. While some fear this approach wastes resources or won't benefit the majority of students, this is incorrect. If we implemented these programs as the standard rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we accomplish this? While requiring all teachers to be bilingual would be unreasonable and impractical, there's no reason we couldn't employ bilingual teaching assistants and tutors to support this approach.

From childhood on, most of us are told there is something greater than ourselves, something beyond our comprehension. Some of us are sent to Sunday school, others attend temple, or search for answers within themselves. Many of us willingly accept the religions passed down from our parents. Others, however, completely reject them, denying that anything beyond the knowable could exist in their own egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values, only to later change our minds and replace it with another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father answered when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on our house's front porch, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above while sharing cigarettes. The gutters channeled the rain down, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain with that look that seemed half-searching, half-remembering. He had grown thinner over recent months, his clothes hanging lifelessly on his frame. His hair had thinned too, sparser than I remembered. He kept staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt lonely, frightened, and unable to tell my father how much I would miss him, because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain in the June twilight.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although primarily a farmer, this profession combined with his brief political career shaped a man known for his commitment and candor in matters of personal liberty and governance. His devotion to an agricultural system formed the foundation for virtually all his views on government. His efforts to preserve and promote what he considered the most noble of all professions influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had an exceptional opportunity to create an ideal system, as there were no established traditions to constrain the nation's founders, thus enabling the establishment of true self-governance. He held strong convictions about natural human rights, believing them to be interconnected—if one right was denied, all would eventually fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. These rights, he maintained, should be beyond government reach. He argued that what some termed the "state of nature" benefited those with physical strength and cunning intelligence, but that civilization must operate differently.

To establish this ideal society, Taylor believed in creating a government that acknowledged humanity's inherent capacity for both good and evil. He maintained strict views on moral dualism, asserting that "Since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He identified good principles as those protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism, believing that a government founded on sound principles would function justly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by self-interest and greed. While he saw self-interest as humanity's universal motivator, he considered it harmful only when it evolved beyond creating a society based on common good into forming sub-societies that exploited others. Good government was essential to contain man's natural tendencies toward evil, though even then it required vigilant oversight to prevent the introduction of harmful principles.

Taylor, like many steadfast Republicans of his era, advocated for strict constitutional interpretation. He favored a highly limited federal government, restricted to only those powers explicitly granted by the Constitution. He understood that an expansive federal government was costly and thus prone to despotism. However, he cautioned against overly simplistic, literal interpretation, arguing that without considering the founders' intent, such an approach could become corrupted. Moreover, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true charter, as it more clearly depicted the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single unified nation.

Downward I gazed, my mind blankly processing the scene before me. With detached observation and practiced awareness, I studied the sight before my eyes, refusing to connect it to any deeper understanding. Thoughts flowed through my consciousness, appearing and disappearing almost instantly. My mind worked with such fluid efficiency that it seemed I had no distinct thoughts of my own, only a dynamic, flowing experience of what I was observing.

Once, following an artist's recommendation, I bought an instructional book titled "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since age six, I had yearned to learn drawing, and this book covered everything from basic pencil handling to understanding how the brain processes visual information. One key technique involved placing a frame around the subject matter, effectively transforming complex scenes - like a fruit bowl in a kitchen connected to a dining room - into manageable compositions, such as simply a bowl of fruit on a plane.

In that moment, looking down at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally construct that artist's frame. I was too overwhelmed, too astounded to do anything but stand and stare in amazement. While Picasso had his blue period, Monet his fascination with greenery, and Renaissance masters their spectrum of colors, if I were to claim any artistic merit, this would be the beginning of my masterpiece: "Work in Brown."

My fingertips touched my chosen artistic tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, my intentions taking physical form in what might have been my most creative moment. Water swirled serenely, crystal clear and pristine. Particles separated from the whole, drifting away into nothingness. With increasing urgency, my hand struck the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown mass refused to budge, clinging like a slug to the bowl's bottom.

Standing there, mop loosely held, feet shoulder-width apart, green tie uncomfortably tight around my neck, I slightly frowned at the crude deposit of processed organic matter someone had left as a "gift" for the Rite Aid bathroom cleaners. After several more flushes and moments of quiet contemplation, my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it resembled a protective mitt. Standing straight, then bending at the waist, my hand descended slowly into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Young people are dying behind the wheel. Multiple factors contribute to this deadly statistical trend among America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem lies in the fact that the adolescent brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Lack of experience is also at the core of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in a higher rate of vehicle rollovers, excessive speeding, and running off the road.

Teenagers also perform significantly worse when traveling with their peers—something anyone with common sense knows happens regularly. Research from the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has demonstrated a clear correlation between passenger age and accident frequency.

California and other states have tried to enhance teen driver safety by implementing provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit minor passengers. However, in my view, provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The fundamental issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical measures, simply not capable of adequately managing the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. According to USA Today, Zuckerman's research indicates a common tendency among those under 19-20 to seek thrills purely for the sensation.

The legislation I propose is straightforward and not unprecedented. While schools could continue providing driver's education to prepare future drivers, no one under 18 would be permitted to operate a motor vehicle. A provisional license system could remain in place before granting full driving privileges, with required practical training hours based on existing state standards. Given that teen driving statistics are problematic across all states, uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and potentially effective approach to protecting young people throughout the country.

This paper examines three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it provides a concise definition of the condition. Following this, it explains the diagnostic process, including common indicators or "warning signs." The paper concludes by discussing methods that educators can employ to support CAPD students in mainstream classroom settings.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), describes how effectively the central nervous system processes auditory information. According to the American Speech-Language-Hearing Association (2005), it specifically relates to how the brain perceives and processes sound information, including the underlying neurobiological activities that generate electrophysiological auditory responses. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing ability but struggle with how their brain processes and interprets sound information, particularly in distinguishing speech from background noise or separating different sounds.

The condition was first documented in the mid-1950s under the term "auditory imperception" during studies of children with communication disorders. In 1954, an Italian research team comprising Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari pioneered testing methods, followed by Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing in 1961, which explained the physiological basis of auditory perception. A significant national conference in 1977 sparked increased research into CAPD in children.

CAPD presents various symptoms: difficulty locating sounds in space, problems distinguishing between different sound events, inability to recognize sound patterns, challenges in detecting vocal nuances like sarcasm, auditory masking (where one sound blocks another), difficulties in processing sound information meaningfully, and problems with sequencing auditory information.

Diagnosis requires comprehensive screening through systematic observation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests. Various professionals, including audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists, may conduct these assessments using different evaluation methods. Currently, there is no single standardized diagnostic tool, and the condition's cause remains unknown. Diagnostic procedures often involve tests with multiple simultaneous audio stimuli, requiring patients to differentiate specific elements like word or number sequences. More sophisticated diagnostic methods include measuring acoustic responses within the ear.

In pursuing my education in social work, I aim to pursue a career with the Department of Family and Children's Services to assist abused or neglected children and support struggling families. The values I can bring to the field of social work include: service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and commitment to my own professional development to maintain competence in my field. These core values are not just important for social workers; they hold deep personal significance for me.

I have always felt drawn to helping others, though I was initially uncertain about my career direction. During my high school and college years, I observed many individuals avoiding their problems through denial or adopting less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. These observations led me to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about my career path after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took some time off. That summer, a pivotal moment occurred when I met a sixteen-year-old boy at a friend's house, seeking refuge from abusive parents. The incident that followed, involving police intervention and my attempt to help mediate the situation, crystallized my decision to pursue social work, particularly to assist children dealing with what some might dismiss as "simple" family disputes.

Social justice represents another crucial value in social work. While our society claims to value individuality and mourns the loss of individuals, we often conform to archaic traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. I have always questioned why we strive for conformity while claiming to value individuality. Throughout my academic years, I actively challenged social injustice through various forms of personal expression: sporting unconventional hair colors, wearing clothing that reflected my personality, getting multiple ear piercings, openly supporting GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and confronting racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. My commitment to social justice remains unwavering, and I will continue to stand against social inequity.

The following paper examines the biological and sociocultural models in relation to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model concentrates on inherited genetic information as well as medical aspects of health. The sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia examines these models and explains each piece of selected research to relate to and better explain the models. The research explanations and their findings are then evaluated to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be categorized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder connected to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other conditions...

I've been studying at University Park for approximately two and a half years now, equivalent to four and a half semesters. Getting around campus poses a challenge for many students, myself included. During my freshman year, I was assigned to East Halls - practically at the easternmost edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The journey from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant buildings like Willard, near campus center, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, particularly during State College's frequently adverse weather conditions.

A conversation with a recent alumnus revealed that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Today, that space has been transformed with athletic fields, substantial new structures including the new Creamery and health services building, and is now surrounded by apartment complexes. As our campus continues its expansion, transportation becomes increasingly challenging. What's the ideal solution to this mobility issue? On a university campus, the answer lies in bicycles. However, bikes alone aren't the complete solution - students need to utilize them, and the campus infrastructure must be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I recently spoke with a friend who had returned to cycling after several years away from it. He expressed surprise at having ever stopped, saying, "Bikes are fantastic - there was a period when cycling wasn't considered cool, but it's really the most practical way to get around." Beyond its health benefits, cycling represents the most efficient mode of transportation. With just a bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort, you can cover 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now reside off-campus, at a distance comparable to some dormitories from the center of campus. Purchasing a bicycle has been my most prudent decision this year. My daily classes in Thomas building would normally require a twenty-five-minute walk from my residence, but cycling reduces this to just 5 minutes at a good pace. The only drawback is that Pollock Road, while offering the most direct route to Thomas building from my home, can be challenging to navigate, whether on bike or foot. While walking has its merits, my schedule simply doesn't allow for it. Without my bicycle, walking would be my only dependable option for reaching classes. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an additional 30-40 minutes - that's over two and a half hours weekly. Factor in all the other walking time for various classes and appointments, and it amounts to more time than I can afford to spend.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat of both technology and capitalistic structures through the creation of a dystopia in "Brave New World." In this world, community value supersedes individual worth, and citizens are conditioned from birth to pursue instant gratification above all else. These citizens emerge as mere pieces in a grand scheme, bound by the ideology imposed by the World Controller. When analyzed through Marxist theory, the author's underlying skepticism toward these developing systems becomes apparent. Common Marxist concepts such as homogeneity and reification strengthen the argument that Huxley's novel serves as commentary on the flaws in his era's emerging economic system.

Capitalism receives satirical treatment through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The general population remains ignorant of their true economic relationship with other classes, focused solely on personal gain. This stems from ideological control of the working class, clearly demonstrated through the conditioning in Brave New World. The lower castes - Delta, Gamma, and others - lack genuine free will; hypnopaedia reinforces their drive to consume, spend, and indulge. The World Controller manipulates this behavior. Hegemony - the complete dominance of social classes by an elite group - is evidently at work. Lower classes remain oblivious to their manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that perpetuates the system. Upper classes possess awareness of this reality but remain passive; few Alphas or Betas, apart from characters like Bernard, challenge their assigned roles. Indeed, class interactions throughout the novel powerfully illustrate capitalism's perceived oppression.

Genuine interpersonal relationships are notably absent in Brave New World. Characters lack individual depth, even among principal figures. Huxley appears to suggest that the combined forces of technology and capitalism strip humanity of autonomy and self-expression. Love is nonexistent, as are intense emotions of any kind. Instead, interactions remain superficial, illustrated by men's focus on women's physical attributes (their "pneumatic" qualities) and women's casual discussion of their encounters. Moreover, each social class's contentment with their hierarchical position reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering acceptance of their community roles mirrors Marxist observations about the proletariat, who are deluded into feeling superior as long as they continue consuming, obeying, and conforming to peer expectations.

Almost four years ago, I enrolled in an Islamic course at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally witnessed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance towards Islam in America. I don't think we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama in 2001, someone with such an obvious Muslim family background.

The Prophet's biography intrigues me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his personality. From my previous knowledge, I believed Muhammad had forced people to convert to Islam. He conquered and took over tribes, then compelled them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a kind of martyr who was misunderstood and even showed humility before others. Subsequently, people came one by one to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

The striking similarities between Jesus's ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles' are particularly noteworthy. The most obvious example is when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men abundantly. This writing style leads me to believe the authors wanted to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This kind of fallacy is particularly troubling because it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems like an attempt to appropriate Jesus's life and personality through Muhammad.

The biography contains many stories that appear designed to provide 'witness' accounts or examples of people converting to Islam 'of their own accord.' However, many of these stories are told from at least a third-hand perspective, with authors citing chains of "heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so." Rather than strengthening the credibility of these accounts, I found this approach made them seem more suspicious and less reliable.

What troubles me most about this work is its attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle man. Historical accounts contradict this portrayal of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true historical circumstances of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and convictions of Jesus during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thought following his death. Looking at this history in broad terms, we observe Christianity increasingly diverging from its origins. Today's world demonstrates an ever-growing consciousness and an unprecedented progressive inclination. While traditionalists persist and will resist thinking beyond their learned beliefs, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will greatly expand in the years to come. A desire will emerge to separate later doctrinal additions from the original intentions of the religion's founder. Though it may take generations or centuries, the outcome is inevitable: A great reversal in Christian historical development will occur. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow that systematically removes layers of doctrine, as if turning back time, until only Jesus's original divine message to humanity remains, free from later interpretations. When this movement sweeps through America and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as in Jesus's time, following only his teachings, the church as an institution will remain strong as a guide. However, as theological time reverses, the extreme diversity in Christianity will consolidate into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Instead of differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, we will see increasing commonality. Human history is full of such reversals - consider how Christians went from being persecuted by the Roman Empire to the Empire itself becoming Christian, or how America transformed from enslaving African-Americans to having African-American leadership. This coming great reversal will unfold within Christianity, undoing historical accretions in search of its source, while reducing diversity. Crucially, this process will be facilitated by reading Jesus's words metaphorically rather than literally. So what has transpired since Jesus's time? Looking far enough back, we find only Judaism as Christianity's theological foundation. Monotheism, the concept of divine revelation, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE. The Jewish population was not unified but divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I contend that "The Jungle" demonstrates humanity's inherently greedy and self-centered nature. People fundamentally focus on their own welfare and advancement, rarely considering those beneath them. This theme manifests throughout the novel, most notably in the behavior of factory owners and managers. These individuals are singularly focused on expanding their enterprises and operations, showing complete disregard for any collateral damage their progress might cause.

As Upton Sinclair vividly describes, "The line of buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Through this imagery, Sinclair illustrates the devastating environmental impact of industrialization. The owners demonstrate no concern for human or animal welfare, whether it's the toxic smoke pouring from their chimneys or the waste from countless animal pens contaminating Packingtown.

The exploitation extends to their workforce, who toil to generate their wealth. As the text reveals, "From top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers face brutal hours and could be terminated without notice or assistance, leaving them destitute. In this era, the absence of labor laws or regulations allowed management to operate unchecked, forcing workers into hazardous conditions and unreasonable productivity demands.

The residents of Packingtown were expected to endure these deplorable conditions both at work and in their communities, with no support systems or advocacy organizations to protect them. While labor unions existed, they often exploited rather than helped the workers. The working class's desperate situation was likened to slavery: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-land stands among Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed superior poems. In "Dream-land," Poe employs the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces to Virgil. While Virgil used this term to reference an island north of Britain, which Greeks considered the edge of the known world, there exists a more contemporary source worthy of acknowledgment. Poe showed considerable interest in German authors.

Goethe was a celebrated author of the poetic drama Faust. Within Faust Part 2, one finds the poem "The King of Thule." The similarities between Poe's "Dream-Land" and Goethe's "King of Thule" are remarkable. Both works explore themes of loss, solitude, and death. Poe used the term "Thule" twice in his collected works, and the connection to Goethe is clearly discernible. Poe was familiar with Goethe's work not only through his admiration for Tennyson but also through the numerous reproductions that emerged following the original publication.

Under California law, the question arises whether a customer who was injured after slipping on spilled applesauce in a grocery store could be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted maliciously, given that he was informed twice about the spill but failed to have it cleaned for thirty minutes because he was eating dinner.

A judge would likely not dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim outright. To justify punitive damages, a plaintiff must demonstrate that the defendant's actions showed willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, while also proving the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the likely harm of an uncleaned spill, especially given that multiple D&D customers had suffered slip-and-fall injuries in previous months. While her argument about the despicable nature of Martin's actions may be less compelling, it remains reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and Martin's continued failure to maintain store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager Paul Martin about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin, who was on his dinner break, dismissed the concern, stating he "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." Fifteen minutes later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 PM, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. The store had already recorded five slip-and-fall incidents earlier that year. Palmer is now pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages, and we are evaluating whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

California law permits punitive damages for non-contractual obligations if the defendant demonstrated "oppression, fraud or malice" (Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a)). The statute defines malicious conduct as either intentionally harmful or, lacking direct intent, "despicable" and showing "willful and conscious disregard for others' rights or safety." Courts have interpreted malicious conduct as actions taken with conscious disregard when the defendant "recognized the probable dangerous consequences of their behavior yet willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences" (Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co.).

She had always sensed an emptiness within her, a yearning that refused to be satisfied. It began around the age of 14, just as she was entering her teenage years, and persisted three years later at 17. By then, she had realized she was searching for someone rather than something. Yet no boys caught her interest, though several had been drawn to her, making awkward attempts to court the un-courtable. She often questioned this peculiarity, trying to understand what could cause such an unusual situation in a teenage girl. Years of reflection had produced theories, but none satisfactory enough to seriously consider. So she continued living, perpetually questioning her desires.

Life at home was typically serene. Her parents were gentle, balanced people who rarely argued, either with each other or with their daughter. The only occasional conflicts arose from her assertions of independence and free spirit. Though born to such peaceful parents, she balanced their calm nature with her vibrant and engaging personality, making her well-liked, especially given her inherent kindness.

But today was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking inspiration, she heard her mother's beautiful voice release a sharp scream from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic rising as she called out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, clearly in pain, breathing shallow "ows" between breaths. Her daughter knelt beside her, reaching out to help. "Ouch... sweet-heart, I... need you to take me to... the hospital," her mother managed between pained gasps. "Okay Mom, just show me where I can lift you." Her mother guided her hands, and at that moment, the household's hero was deeply thankful for her strength training classes. She carried her mother to the car, carefully laid her in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital visit brought its typical mix of antiseptic smells and illness, tinged with anxiety. But she noticed none of it, focused entirely on helping her mother. She carried her in swiftly, calling out for medical assistance. Concerned staff quickly gathered, transferring her mother onto a gurney. They whisked her away for immediate examination, leaving her daughter to wait in worried solitude.

The cause? Her mother had fallen from a stepstool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," correlates with lower risks of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet represents a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but encompassing fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (versus saturated fats) and fish, while reducing consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse relationship between Mediterranean diet adherence and overall cardiovascular (CVD) mortality rates. An intervention trial demonstrated the Mediterranean diet's superiority over low-fat diets in achieving weight loss and improving the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese subjects. However, previous research had not specifically addressed stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological investigation tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated aMed diet scores six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year study period. FFQs underwent validation studies, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical records, hospital documentation, autopsies, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were designated as "probable" and included, comprising approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions.

To minimize random individual variation and better represent long-term dietary patterns, cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs were calculated. The study controlled for confounding factors by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling evaluated the relationship between aMed scores and CHD and stroke risk, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal events.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, reflected by elevated aMed diet scores, was associated with reduced risk of both CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, researchers documented 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile demonstrated lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone at a street corner, holding a piece of cardboard above her head with this disturbing message scrawled in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a tyrannical military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, several street protests erupted, marking the first public demonstrations in ten years. These protests, led by numerous Burmese monks, became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. Following the initial uprising, the general public began taking interest in the protests. While the Burmese government initially reluctantly permitted the monks to hold peaceful gatherings, the situation soon escalated into what some described as an outright war between the monks and the military junta, with forces actively raiding and pillaging monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were immediately arrested upon discovery, with Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, merely for being present at a protest. Though the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army shortly before the official report, stated, "The number of people killed in recent days far exceeds what's been reported. The death toll runs into several thousand."

This pattern is not unprecedented. While these represent some of the most recent examples of atrocities in our world, governments' desire to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their populations has existed throughout civilization. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine right to exercise complete control over their society. Japanese emperors were believed to be actual deities, sent to guide their people to prosperity through developments like Motorola phones and ritual suicide, while our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly discussions with Ted Haggard, who leads Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Among the most notorious examples are the June 4th, 1989 protest in Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, workers, and students gathered to protest authoritarian rule. Casualty figures for this event vary dramatically, from official Chinese government reports of 200-300 deaths to Chinese Red Cross estimates of 2,000-3,000 fatalities. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s represents another instance, where Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, systematically eliminated Tutsis and political moderates regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning multiple years and countries during which Jewish people were systematically rounded up and killed, serves as another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's jazz legacy stems largely from his longevity and, consequently, his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While Ellington's piano presence remains subtle in many of the compositions discussed here, his brilliance as a composer shone through in creating rich, complex pieces that highlighted his band members' individual talents. Ellington masterfully crafted frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also composing tightly orchestrated passages that leveraged band members' unique styles to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he enhanced the orchestra's overall tonality, creating distinctive and cohesive sounds tailored to each piece. His profound understanding of individual players' sounds and their collective harmony in an expanding ensemble enabled him to compose some of jazz history's most groundbreaking and brilliant works.

The Grove Music dictionary notes Ellington's sonic innovation, particularly referencing Creole Love Call as an example of his pioneering use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This early work demonstrates Ellington's skill in using vocals to add texture and color without lyrics, while showcasing his ability to complement his soloists' styles - a trait evident throughout his career. This measured, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece unfolds across six choruses:

Chorus 1: A vocal-reed call and response, beginning smoothly and melodically before transitioning to a rougher texture.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo expanding on the core melody with extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A soaring high-register clarinet solo supported by subtle syncopated piano.
Chorus 4: Full ensemble echoing the first chorus through brass and reed section call and response.
Chorus 5: The piece's climax, featuring high-register reed calls and responses backed by syncopated brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returning to the initial structure, but with the voice adopting a "growl" technique as an instrumental soloist.
Tag: Concluding with a vocal run and distinctive trombone dissonance.

This vocal approach to tonal color became a hallmark of Ellington's style. In Hot and Bothered, recorded the following year, Ellington merged precise orchestration with tonal exploration. The call-and-response between "Bubber" Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing creates a rich harmony by blending vocal and instrumental qualities. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) further develops these concepts, featuring Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's masterful muted trombone introduction of the melody.

Why do organisms develop in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "zoologists have barely begun to define even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this statement remains valid today. In recent times, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeleton formation through both ontogeny and phylogeny.

A shell can be understood as a tube-like structure that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These rotations or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the shell's central column, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and a continuous line known as the suture separates each whorl. In most shells, the final whorl (body whorl) is the largest. The spire comprises all whorls except the last one. The apex marks the spire's tip, while the opposite end is called the base. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. The standard orientation shows the shell in an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.

The shell can be viewed as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal constructs its shell. This growth pattern can be tracked using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically, allowing for parameter variation and modification of mollusk skeletogenesis in theoretical models.

The infant and child mortality rate in Indonesia has remained relatively stable over the past decade. While the country is progressing toward achieving many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvement rates for child and maternal health fall far short of the progress needed to meet their 2015 targets. The various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed below, suggesting the need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has shown progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional practitioners, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in cases of complicated pregnancies (explaining the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). In other words, the improvements in this particular indicator are somewhat deceptive, and substantial work remains to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five being treated by healthcare professionals. While postnatal care data is incomplete, it's evident that this area is also problematic, with low rates throughout the country.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at around 4%. These rates also highlight another concerning issue: while urban areas show a 7% c-section rate, rural areas only show 2%. This demonstrates an equity problem in healthcare coverage across the country, with healthcare services clearly concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poor evidently face greater difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to most effectively address the service gap. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing exclusively on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches to address these issues are appealing, offering more targeted, manageable objectives and typically faster results, they come with notable drawbacks. One major concern is that heavy investment in one health sector's programming often depletes funding for other areas and attracts human resources away from other sectors (as seen in international HIV/AIDS funding's impact on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

The categorization of popular music has expanded so dramatically over the last 100 years that it now encompasses so many genres that it's challenging to definitively list them all. Making matters more complex, most if not all genres - rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, to name just a few - have given rise to multiple sub-genres and sub-sub-genres within their domain. The sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has arguably become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in all of popular music over the past 40 years. It's expressive because it showcases a wide range of emotions, though they tend to gravitate toward the darker end of the spectrum. Its diversity stems from the fact that shortly after the genre's inception, people recognized its inherent flexibility and began utilizing it to create their own sub-genres, which in turn led to sub-sub-genres, a progression that continues to this day.

We've now reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many specialized niches that defining heavy metal itself has become challenging. While it has incorporated numerous themes from other genres, like everything else, it originated from somewhere. To properly understand the metal music that pervades today's world, one must first grasp what the metal movement is and why it's considered a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement characterized by darkness. It can be seen as a "music of more" - more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitiveness, more technical skill; metal musicians are typically highly proficient with their instruments, which is evident in their music. Metal is also - perhaps unsurprisingly - a movement heavily influenced by drugs. The psychedelic drug boom of the mid-70s led to increasingly experimental approaches, resulting in otherworldly recordings, with drugs often serving as both inspiration and explanation for their creation.

Several decades before the Surrealist artists began creating their dream-like works, the artist Henri Rousseau was crafting his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, depicts not only a woman in wonderment at the marvels of the land she visits within a dream, but also embodies Rousseau's personal aspirations and goals as a painter. From the beginning of his artistic journey, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, finding himself faced with a profound internal struggle to achieve this ambition. "The Dream" is Henri Rousseau's work that most powerfully reflects his lifelong inner conflict: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to remain creatively independent and unique, forging his own path as he went.

Before analyzing "The Dream" through this lens, one must understand something of Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwestern France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed middle-class comfort. Having received no formal artistic training, he worked until age forty as a gabelou (municipal toll collector), though he was mistakenly nicknamed douanier (customs inspector). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the losses of eight infant children, left Rousseau with just one surviving daughter, Julia, and overwhelming grief. He sought solace in a new life, turning to painting for comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized peasant life in their paintings, Rousseau was essentially a folk artist who shared the hopes and dreams of his social class.

Many great thinkers have proposed a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this relationship. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all you know on earth, and all you need to know." While much of our knowledge comes through education or experience, our appreciation of ethics and aesthetics seems to develop, as Keats suggests, without conventional teaching methods.

Both ethics and aesthetics are descriptive rather than prescriptive endeavors. Our studies of morality and beauty are primarily attempts to explain why art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than establishing rules for judging or creating good art or ethical behavior.

More importantly, critiques of art or morality can never fully capture the essence of goodness or beauty. While we might discuss the Mona Lisa in terms of technique, composition, or cultural context, these elements alone don't explain what makes it great art. People often preface their analysis of favorite artwork or literature with "There's just something about it" before delving into more detailed explanations. I believe both art and morality resist complete reduction to their constituent qualities. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Something transcendent remains beyond even the most thorough analysis of literature, and ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein observes, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." I propose that this ineffable quality, this je ne sais quoi, is the most powerful attribute of both art and morality, and creates a bridge between them.

The connection between morality and art is particularly strong because we experience both most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use Kant's terminology. They affect us in ways we can experience but cannot fully explain. This connection is especially evident in literature. As McKean observes, literature's distinctive feature is its moral quality, setting it apart from other art forms. While moral standards might not apply to all arts, such as music, they are as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature's significance lies precisely in the values we discover within it.

Today's Germany is regarded as a powerful force, a unified nation with its own unique cultural blend stretching from the shadow of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic coastal city of Kiel. This same culture can be experienced from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's heartland, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe River. Given such a distinctive culture, it's not surprising that the Germany we know today emerged from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the German people. The origin of its name remains a subject of intense debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungri, who were called Germans before crossing the Rhine and engaging in battle with Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first employed the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought against Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine with hostile intentions. He adopted this term from the Gauls themselves, using it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not.

The play Twelfth Night appears to suggest that while disguise can serve as a useful tool for sustained deception, one must ultimately shed this adopted persona or risk losing their authentic self in the process. A significant challenge in ending such deception lies in the potential alienation that follows. Thus, one must ultimately choose between preserving their true identity and maintaining their relationships with others. While some might react indifferently to discovering they've been deceived, others will take offense at the masquerade and respond with hurt and anger.

The matter of gender-based deception proves particularly complex, raising numerous secondary concerns, chief among them being the motivation. What drives an individual to abandon their identity and assume the disguise of another gender? In Viola's case, it clearly stems from self-preservation: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249)

Finding herself in unfamiliar territory, Viola adopts a male persona as a shield against potential threats. While this strategy proves effective, it also isolates her from female companionship, depriving her of vital social support. The situation grows more complicated when her masculine portrayal proves so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love: "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she must navigate the complex romantic tension with Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261)

While modern audiences might find this treatment somewhat progressive, Twelfth Night can be interpreted as demonstrating how deception can catalyze the emergence of repressed emotions, particularly in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Certain passages suggest these characters harbor unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. One might question whether Olivia's attraction to Cesario stems from his apparent masculinity, or if it reveals latent same-sex desires. However, it seems more likely that Shakespeare uses Olivia's character to satirize those who judge purely on appearances.

This interpretation is supported by how easily Olivia transfers her affections from Cesario to Sebastian, ultimately coming to view Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been criticized by various observers for its brutality, particularly regarding the genocide of the Herero and Nama people in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast colonial empire cannot be characterized by such a simple description. The German colonial empire exhibited as much diversity in its policies and governing styles as it did in its geography. Educational provisions across the colonies showed similar variation. When the British took control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a substantial population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies also received praise from contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) stood in marked contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and took an active role in native education, in South West Africa the education of indigenous peoples was almost entirely delegated to missionary societies with minimal government support. The government did, however, invest considerable resources in European education in the colony, establishing state schools and providing stronger support and oversight for missionary schools serving the white population. These educational policies had lasting implications for South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies could boast significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's divergent experience. This study aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors, with particular emphasis on new research regarding settler and colonial authority attitudes toward native Africans.

There exists extensive literature on education in the German colonial empire. Most sources are in German and date from the early twentieth century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. Early works primarily aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language studies expanded the discourse through comparative analyses of education across German colonies and more detailed examinations of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant variations in colonial educational systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa stands as the most notable work directly addressing this paper's topic. Cohen's comparative analysis of the two colonies' educational systems explores the factors behind their differences, attributing many of South West Africa's distinctive educational characteristics to its large settler population.

Compared to Germany's other colonial territories, South West Africa enjoyed a relatively temperate climate, despite much of its territory being arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these comparatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The United States of America and Mexico exemplify two nations that were once characterized by a persistent rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The pinnacle of this rivalry manifested in the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States defeated Mexico and acquired Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other confrontations occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before World War I.

The rivalry originated from fundamental conflicts between Americans and Mexicans regarding religion, culture, and traditions, coupled with significant clashes over material interests. This pattern mirrors many other nations experiencing enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders typically face conflicting interests that foster rivalrous relationships. As David M. Pletcher noted in 1977, "Only Mexico and Cuba presented long-lasting, comprehensive diplomatic challenges for America." Indeed, both nations' proximity to the United States contributed to their rival status, while other Latin American nations maintained generally positive relations with the United States.

Religious differences created a significant divide between the two nations, a common historical pattern. As Sally Frahm observed, American opposition to Catholicism and monarchy in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries paralleled their later resistance to fascism and communism in the twentieth century. Similar to the ideological component of the Cold War between the United States and Soviet Union, this rivalry combined ideological differences with competition over vital national interests, though the ideological element centered on religious rather than political differences. This mutual distrust originated from historical English-Spanish antagonism, inherited from their colonial predecessors.

During the 57-year rivalry period, Diehl and Goerts documented 17 distinct disputes between Mexico and the United States. Most conflicts involved territorial issues, particularly border raids and frontier challenges. Both nations eventually deployed military forces to address the persistent problem of bandits and outlaws targeting border towns.

The rivalry gradually diminished as Mexico became increasingly economically dependent on the United States, and American priorities shifted from territorial expansion to economic involvement in Mexico during the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

I was a nurse back then. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply rooted need for safety and security that I lacked as a child. "You'll always find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So - even though my dream was to be a scientist or journalist - preferably both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, with barely any savings and unable to work. To this day I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left I can call my own. I get by, but each day is a struggle that challenges my security, safety, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is certain anymore, one thing remains true: I couldn't have survived all these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And trust me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

The point I'm making is that life will always bring emergencies - both big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some challenges are simply too great to overcome alone.

I wholeheartedly agree that we in the U.S. need to stop placing all our trust in big government's "basket" - heaven knows it's already moldy and falling apart. However, I'd much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again - learning to help each other and ask for help - rather than having everyone retreat to their backyards to build individual fallout shelters.

American Conservatives speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in truth, what sustained our ancestors through hard times wasn't rugged individualism - it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit: first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting with duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have multiple flashlights and various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food - do it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're preparing for all this, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly attachments and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—with its most orthodox branch known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now approximately twenty-five centuries old, appears quite different today from how it existed during Buddha's time. This transformation is evident everywhere, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance, despite Buddha never having taught about such festivities. These variations extend from surface-level traditions to the soteriological essence of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has needed to adapt its doctrinal principles over time, influenced by forces both external and internal, hostile and benign.

The discussion employs several key qualifying terms. The concept of internal versus external forces is central—internal forces originate from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from negative perceptions of Buddhism. Benign forces neither intend to help nor harm the Buddhist community, though they may inadvertently do either. These distinctions will be crucial throughout the discussion.

To understand these changes, one must first grasp the fundamental doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is primarily contained in the Tripitaka—the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka holds the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka encompasses Buddhism's metaphysical aspects. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Understanding these concepts is essential for ending Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. Along with Sansara's end comes the cessation of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) through enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes life's rules—five precepts for laypeople (abstaining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and intoxicants) and numerous additional rules for monks. The four noble truths form Buddhism's most fundamental doctrine: first, that life contains suffering (Dukkha); second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
